. In our base simulation, annual positive flux trends of 0.2{\%} and 0.52{\%} throughout the entire period are found in Asia and China, respectively, related to a positive trend in temperature and solar radiation. The impact of oil palm expansion in Indonesia and Malaysia is to enhance the trends over that region, e.g., from 1.17{\%} to 1.5{\%} in 1979–2005 in Malaysia. A negative emission trend is derived in India (−0.4{\%}), owing to the negative trend in solar radiation data associated with the strong dimming effect likely due to inc{\ldots}},
author = {Stavrakou, T. and M{\"{u}}ller, J.-F. and Bauwens, M. and {De Smedt}, I. and {Van Roozendael}, M. and Guenther, A. and Wild, M. and Xia, X.},
doi = {10.5194/acp-14-4587-2014},
issn = {1680-7324},
journal = {Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics},
month = {may},
